answers.body_markdown:
In your case, I think you **have** to give an explicit override to resolve the ambiguity! However, it would be an extremely trivial override:
```c++
struct D : A, B {
	// Uncomment the following line to resolve.
	void vf() override { A::vf(); }
};
```
This will just call the `A` base class whenever `D::vf()` is called! Thus, in accordance with your last sentence, there is no problem, as the *&quot;method code in one of the base class&quot;* is used (but you have to specify which base class).

