You should be able to do that with `std::stringstream` and [`std::basic_stringbuf&lt;CharT,Traits,Allocator&gt;::setbuf`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/io/basic_stringbuf/setbuf) but the C++ standard botched its requirements: 

&gt; The effect [of `setbuf`] is implementation-defined: some implementations do nothing, while some implementations clear the `std::string` member currently used as the buffer and begin using the user-supplied character array of size `n`, whose first element is pointed to by `s`, as the buffer and the input/output character sequence.

You used a raw string to define your data. This means that the final string will still contain the backslash. If this was an error the solution is easy.

    &gt;&gt;&gt; template = &quot;Hello, {data}&quot;
    &gt;&gt;&gt; value = &quot;You\&#39;re genius&quot;
    &gt;&gt;&gt; template.format(data=value)
    &quot;Hello, You&#39;re genius&quot;

If you really have a string with an backslash and a single quote you can use [`literal_eval`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/ast.html#ast.literal_eval) but you have to take into account that you&#39;ll have to add quotes at the end and beginning.

    &gt;&gt;&gt; template = &quot;Hello, {data}&quot;
    &gt;&gt;&gt; value = r&quot;You\&#39;re genius&quot;  # the same as value = &quot;You\\&#39;re genius&quot;
    &gt;&gt;&gt; template.format(data=ast.literal_eval(f&#39;&quot;{value}&quot;&#39;))
    &quot;Hello, You&#39;re genius&quot;

If you&#39;re on an older Python version without f-strings you can write

    &gt;&gt;&gt; template.format(data=ast.literal_eval(&#39;&quot;&#39; + value + &#39;&quot;&#39;))

If printing out ```Hello, your\re a genius``` is what you want, is this simple:

```
str1 = &quot;Hello&quot;
str2 = &quot;you\\&#39;re a genius&quot;

formated_str = f&quot;{str1}, {str2}&quot;
```
Which prints: ```Hello, you\&#39;re a genius```

Double backslash will give you an actual backslash on a string.

