As you mentioned the [documentation](https://laravel.com/docs/6.x/authentication#adding-custom-user-providers) suggests implementing a custom user provider. The following steps more or less describe how you&#39;ll tackle it in a bit more detail.

1. Create or edit a [service provider](https://laravel.com/docs/5.8/providers)
You can create a new service provider by running 

```php artisan make:provider CustomAuthServiceProvider```

2. In the `boot` method of your service provider you&#39;ll have to configure our auth provider (which will be implemented in step 4).

```
    public function boot()
    {
        Auth::provider(&#39;custom-auth&#39;, function ($app, array $config) {
            return new CustomAuthProvider();
        });
    }
```

3. Update your `auth.php` configuration to use the serviceprovider we registered in step 2 
```
&#39;providers&#39; =&gt; [
    &#39;users&#39; =&gt; [
        &#39;driver&#39; =&gt; &#39;custom-auth&#39;,
    ],
],
```
4. Create the `CustomAuthProvider` class itself and implement the [UserProvider interface](https://laravel.com/api/5.7/Illuminate/Contracts/Auth/UserProvider.html)
```
class CustomAuthProvider implements UserProvider
{
    public function retrieveById($identifier) {
        // Retrieve a user by their unique identifier.
    }

    public function retrieveByToken($identifier, $token) {
        // Retrieve a user by their unique identifier and &quot;remember me&quot; token.
    }

    public function updateRememberToken(Authenticatable $user, $token) {
        // Update the &quot;remember me&quot; token for the given user in storage.
    }

    public function retrieveByCredentials(array $credentials) {
        // Retrieve a user by the given credentials.
    }

    public function validateCredentials(Authenticatable $user, array $credentials) {
        // Validate a user against the given credentials.
    }
}
```

